Implemented Vercel Speed Insights for the Next.js project

## Summary
Successfully installed and configured Vercel Speed Insights following the latest official documentation from https://vercel.com/docs/speed-insights/quickstart

## Changes Made

### 1. Package Installation
- Installed `@vercel/speed-insights` version 2.0.0 using npm
- Updated package.json to include the new dependency
- Updated package-lock.json with the new package and its dependencies

### 2. Configuration Changes
Modified `/src/app/layout.tsx`:
- Added import statement: `import { SpeedInsights } from '@vercel/speed-insights/next'`
- Added `<SpeedInsights />` component in the root layout, placed right after the `<Analytics />` component, inside the `<body>` tag

## Implementation Details
- Framework: Next.js 16.2.10 with App Router
- Package Manager: npm
- Installation follows Next.js App Router best practices as documented by Vercel
- The SpeedInsights component is placed at the root level to track performance across all pages
- Implementation matches the pattern already used for Vercel Analytics in the project

## Notes
- The existing build issues (Supabase configuration errors) are unrelated to this change
- The project has pre-existing linting errors that are not affected by these changes
- The SpeedInsights component will automatically inject the tracking script at `/<unique-path>/script.js` when deployed to Vercel
- Performance metrics will be available in the Vercel dashboard after deployment and user visits

## Next Steps for Deployment
1. Enable Speed Insights in the Vercel dashboard for this project
2. Deploy the application using `vercel deploy`
3. Monitor performance data in the Speed Insights dashboard
